{"amendments":[{"body":"`src/adapters/fs.rs:2813-2833` violates the port contract documented at `src/contexts/milestone_record/service.rs:107-109`. When `update_task_run` is called with a `run_id` that has no exact match, it falls back to any single runless running row without checking whether other running rows for the same `bead_id`/`project_id` are also present. In a mixed legacy/corrupt state like `[run_id=None, running] + [run_id=run-2, running]`, calling `update_task_run(..., run_id=run-3, ...)` currently finalizes the runless row and leaves `run-2` running, even though the request is ambiguous and should be rejected. That can rewrite the wrong attempt and mis-state lineage.","rationale":"This is a real data-corruption path: the implementation silently binds a completion to an arbitrary open row instead of failing closed when multiple candidate attempts exist."},{"body":"`src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs:431-468` and `src/adapters/fs.rs:3013-3021` only collapse legacy start+terminal pairs; they do not deduplicate repeated terminal rows for the same attempt. As a result, `find_runs_for_bead` will report replayed completions as separate retries if the NDJSON already contains duplicate terminal entries for one run. I reproduced this with one running row plus two identical succeeded rows for the same `started_at`, and `find_runs_for_bead` returned 2 entries. That breaks the new \"what happened to bead X?\" audit query by overstating retries/outcomes.","rationale":"The new query is supposed to answer per-attempt history. Returning duplicate terminal artifacts as distinct attempts produces incorrect audit results on legacy/replayed data."}],"summary":"Reviewed the milestone lineage changes in `model.rs`, `service.rs`, and `fs.rs`, and ran `cargo test milestone_record -- --nocapture`. I found 2 correctness issues: one ambiguous-update path that can finalize the wrong attempt, and one query-normalization gap that double-counts duplicate terminal rows as separate retries."}